Subject: Enable & promote the new EVDI output to primary via kscreen-doctor

Background: MrOz59-Apollo creates an EVDI virtual display via libevdi
(evdi_add_device + evdi_connect with EDID), but does nothing to tell the
desktop compositor to actually USE the new output. On KDE Plasma Wayland
kwin enumerates the new connector but leaves the output disabled.

The downstream effect: Apollo's KMS screencast (kmsgrab.cpp) scans every
/dev/dri/cardN for DRM planes with an attached framebuffer. The EVDI card
has zero planes-with-fb because no compositor draws to it, so KMS capture
falls through to the physical GPU and the Steam Deck ends up streaming the
host's primary monitor instead of a separate virtual desktop.

This patch shells out to `kscreen-doctor` after evdi_connect succeeds:

  1. Snapshot the set of connected outputs BEFORE add+connect.
  2. After evdi_connect, poll kscreen-doctor -j (up to ~3s) for an output
     that is now present but was not before — that is the new EVDI output.
  3. Run:  kscreen-doctor output.<new>.enable output.<new>.priority.1 \
                          output.<old_primary>.priority.2
     This makes kwin actually render desktop content to the EVDI framebuffer,
     which is what kmsgrab then captures.
  4. On removeVirtualDisplay() (refcounted, last-out-restores), put the
     original primary back to priority 1.

Defenses:
  - All output names are validated against a strict [A-Za-z0-9_-]{1,64}
    allowlist before being interpolated into a shell command.
  - If kscreen-doctor isn't installed or the JSON parse fails, we log a
    warning and continue — non-KDE users still get the EVDI device created
    (the first patch's behavior).
  - Static refcount + mutex so two simultaneous virtual displays don't
    each "restore" the primary at the wrong moment.

After this patch, Apollo's Linux EVDI path delivers what users expect:
the Steam Deck sees a separate 1280x800 virtual desktop, and the host's
3440x1440 primary monitor is left undisturbed for the duration of the
streaming session.

